    "recap_headline": "Xavier University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "CINCINNATI\n- Xavier opened its weekend series with Evansville with a 7-5 victory on Friday afternoon at Hayden Field.\nThe Musketeers improved to 6-13 on the year, while the Purple Aces moved to 3-13.\nEvansville took an early 2-0 advantage by scoring a run in each of the first two innings. Xavier responded with a four-run second inning, scoring four runs on three hits and one error.\nMitchell Morton\nand\nJorge Valdes\ndrove in the first two runs before a\nClay Burdette\nhome run down the left-field line scored the final two runs.\nThe Purple Aces tied the game, 4-4, in the top of the fourth inning on a two-out, two-run homer by\u00a0Ximi Baftiri. Xavier responded in the bottom of the frame by scoring three runs on two hits, taking a 7-4 advantage. A\nClay Burdette\ntwo RBI double scored the first two runs before\nJorge Valdes\ncrossed home plate on a\nJosh Stonehouse\nsacrifice fly.\nEvansville closed within two runs, 7-5, when Carlie Long crossed home plate on a RBI ground out by\u00a0Drew McConne.\nXavier's pitching staff threw six strikeouts in the last three innings and did not allow a hit, sealing the two-run victory.\nXavier had four more hits (9-5) than Evansville and left four more runners on base (7-3). Evansville committed the lone error in the game.\nXavier continues its eight-game homestand vs Evansville on Saturday, March 14 in game two of the weekend series. First pitch is set for 2 p.m. from Hayden Field with the game being aired on ESPN+.\nAT THE PLATE\nClay Burdette\nwent 3-for-4 with four RBI, a homer, a double and a run. He now has four multi-hit and multi-RBI games on the season.\nJorge Valdes\nwent 4-for-4 with two runs and a RBI. He now has a .529 batting average in five games this season.\nJosh Stonehouse\nwent 1-for-3 with a double and a RBI. He now has a team-high 15 RBI on the year.\nLuke Hammond\nadded a hit and a run, while\nTanner Thomas\nadded a run.\nDonavan Canterberry\nalso scored two runs.\non the mound\nRyan Piech\n(2-2) went six innings, throwing seven strikeouts and issuing three walks. The RHP allowed five runs and five hits. He now has a season-high 33 strikeouts on the season.\nOwen Poole\nthrew a season-high 2.1 innings of relief. The RHP matched his season high in strikeouts with four. He did not allow a hit or a run to the eight batters he faced.\nKarter Muck\nearned his first save of the season, striking out both batters he faced in the ninth inning.\nXavier's pitching staff threw 13 strikeouts, the second most in a game this season. The Musketeers now have six games on the year with 10 or more strikeouts.\nHIGHLIGHTS"
